definition.value: A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is that is dAMP in which the hydrogen at position 8 of the purine base has been replaced by a hydroxy group.

A branched amino nonasaccharide comprised of a hexasaccharide chain of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, alpha-D-mannose, beta-D-mannose, and two N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked sequentially (1->4), (1->2), (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4), to the beta-D-mannose residue of which is (1->6)-linked a beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-mannosyl trisaccharide branch.
An imidazolyl carboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 1-methylimidazol-5-yl group.

A branched amino decasaccharide consisting of a hexasaccharide chain of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, alpha-D-mannose, beta-D-mannose, and two N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked sequentially (1->4), (1->2), (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4), to the beta-D-mannose residue of which is (1->6)-linked a beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-mannosyl trisaccharide branch and to the reducing end N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residue of which is (1->6)-linked an alpha-L-fucose residue.  When it is the N-glycan content of the tumour necrosis factor (TNF) alpha blocker adalimumab, the two terminal galactose residues may be either absent or alternatively the linkage to the GlcNAc residues may be (1->3), while the fucose residue may be absent.
A sphingoid that is 4-hydroxyhexadecasphinganine substituted at position 15 by a methyl group.

A branched amino heptasaccharide comprised of a hexasaccharide chain of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, alpha-D-mannose, beta-D-mannose, and two N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked sequentially (1->4), (1->2), (1->3), (1->4) and (1->4), to the beta-D-mannose residue of which is (1->6)-linked an alpha-D-mannose residue.
A heptasaccharide derivative having one or more substituted or unsubstituted amino groups in place of hydroxy groups at unspecified positions.
A positively charged methylinosine in which a single methyl substituent is located at position 7 on the hypoxanthine ring.
Inosine carrying a methyl substituent on the oxygen at position 6 on the hypoxanthine ring.
A phthalic acid monoester resulting from the condensation of one of the carboxy groups of phthalic acid with ethanol.

A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid and sulfate groups of the repeating units of heparan sulfate N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminide; major species at pH 7.3.

A carbohydrate acid derivative anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid and sulfate groups of the repeating units of heparan sulfate alpha-D-glucosaminide 3-sulfate; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acetylamino acid that is the N-acetyl derivative of tryptophan.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the amino groups of any alkane-alpha,omega-diamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is oleanane containing a double bond between positions 12 and 13 and substituted by hydroxy groups at the 3beta, 16alpha and 28-positions.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as isobutryl.
A lactoyl-CoA(4-) in which the lactoyl residue has (R)-configuration.
Pterin carrying a formyl group at position 6.
Any entity used to generate reactive oxygen species.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of 4-hydroxy-15-methylhexadecasphinganine, obtained by protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as isovaleryl.
The pteridine that is lumazine reduced across the C-6,C-7-double bond and substituted with a hydroxymethyl group at C-6 and a 1-D-ribityl group at N-8.
A hexacyclic triterpenoid that consists of oleanane substituted by hydroxy groups at 3beta and 16alpha-position and an oxolane bridge at positions 13 and 28.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the free amino group of any N-monoacetylalkane-alpha,omega-diamine; major species at pH 7.3.
Cytidine in which one of the exocyclic amino hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid functions of 3-hydroxyadipyl-CoA.
An anionic phospholipid that is the conjugate base of 15-methylhexadecasphing-4-enine, having an anionic phosphate group and a protonated amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A cardenolide glycoside in which the parent structure gitoxigenin is glycosylated at the 3beta-hydroxy group by beta-D-digitalose.
A benzenetriol that is benzene-1,2,4-triol substituted by a pentadecyl group at position 6.
A triterpenoid that consists of a hexacyclic ring system.
An enal consisting of tetradec-2-enal substituted at position 13 by a methyl group.
A cardenolide glycoside that is gitoxin in which the 16beta-hydroxy group has been formylated.
A C9-acylcarnitine having nonanoyl as the acyl substituent.
An agonist that binds to and activates G-protein-coupled receptors
A benzenetriol that is benzene-1,2,4-triol substituted by a (8Z)-pentadec-8-en-1-yl group at position 6.
A cardenolide glycoside consisting of digitoxigenin having an alpha-L-rhamnosyl moiety attached at the O(3)-position.
A benzenetriol that is benzene-1,2,4-triol substituted by a (8Z,11Z)-heptadeca-8,11-dien-1-yl moiety at position 6.
A cardanolide glycoside that is the 20,22-dihydro derivative of digoxin.
A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of octanoic (caprylic) acid with the anomeric hydroxy group of beta-D-glucuronic acid.
A hydroxy steroid that is the 20,22-dihydro derivative of digoxigenin, consisting of 5beta-cardanolide with hydroxy groups at the 3beta-, 12beta- and 14beta-positions.
A 3-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is 3-hydroxydecanoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 4 (the 3S,4S stereoisomer).
A cardenolide glycoside that is the 12-acetate of digoxin.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of 3-dehydrohexadecasphinganine, obtained by protonation of the primary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of 3-dehydrotetradecasphinganine, obtained by protonation of the primary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of hexadecasphinganine, obtained by protonation of the primary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of tetradecasphinganine, obtained by protonation of the primary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
A cationic sphingoid that is the conjugate acid of hexadecasphing-4-enine, obtained by protonation of the primary amino function; major species at pH 7.3.
An  octenoyl-Lcarnitine having 2-octenoyl as the acyl substituent.
